  "passage_id": "AUSTEN_EMMA_010",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "Emma felt regret; the prospect of showing courtesy to someone she disliked for three long months was daunting! She felt she would constantly be doing more than she desired, yet less than she should. Explaining her aversion to Jane Fairfax was not simple; Mr. Knightley had once suggested it stemmed from seeing in Jane the truly accomplished woman Emma wished to be considered herself. Although she had quickly denied the charge, during moments of introspection, her conscience struggled to fully clear her. Yet, she felt she could never truly know her: she could not explain it, but there was such a chilling reserve—such a clear lack of concern about being agreeable—and then, her aunt was such a relentless chatterbox! Furthermore, everyone made such a fuss over her, and it had always been assumed they would be close friends, simply because they were the same age, leading everyone to expect they must be fond of one another. These were her justifications; she had no others.\n\nIt was an unfair dislike, as every perceived flaw was exaggerated by her imagination, so she never encountered Jane Fairfax after a long separation without feeling she had wronged her. Now, as she paid the required visit upon Jane’s arrival after two years, she was particularly impressed by the very appearance and demeanor she had spent those two years criticizing. Jane Fairfax was truly elegant, remarkably so, and Emma held elegance in the highest regard. Her stature was pleasing, of a height most would call tall, yet none would consider excessive; her form was notably graceful, and her build was a flattering balance between thin and stout, though a slight pallor hinted at the former being the more likely concern. Emma could not help but notice all this; and then, her face and features possessed more beauty than she had recalled. It was not perfectly regular, but it was a very attractive beauty. Her deep grey eyes, framed by dark lashes and brows, had always been admired, but the complexion she had previously criticized for lacking color possessed a clarity and refinement that required no additional glow. It was a style of beauty defined by elegance, and as such, her own principles compelled her to admire it—an elegance of person and mind that she found so rarely in Highbury. In that place, merely avoiding vulgarity was considered a mark of distinction and merit.\n\nIn essence, during that initial visit, she sat observing Jane Fairfax with a dual sense of satisfaction, feeling both pleasure and the gratification of being fair, and she resolved to dislike her no longer. Indeed, when she reflected on her history and circumstances alongside her beauty, and considered the future awaiting such elegance—the life she was destined to descend into—it seemed impossible to feel anything but sympathy and respect, especially if one added to the well-known facts that earned her interest the highly probable notion of an attachment to Mr. Dixon, which she had so naturally begun to suspect."
}

