  "rewritten_text": "Everyone was so joyful, and she and her dance partner were the most joyful of all! “I predicted it would turn out this way,” served as her sole comfort. Her father’s perspective was entirely different. He focused mainly on Mrs. Churchill’s health, inquiring about her medical care; regarding the dance, he found it dreadful that dear Emma was let down, yet he felt they would all be more secure staying indoors. Emma was prepared for her guest well before he arrived; however, if this cast doubt on his eagerness, his mournful expression and complete lack of energy upon arrival surely made up for it. He found the departure almost too painful to discuss. His gloom was unmistakable. He remained silent and lost in reflection for several moments; when he finally stirred, it was merely to remark, “Of all dreadful experiences, saying goodbye is the most terrible.” “But you shall return,” Emma insisted. “This will not be your final trip to Randalls.” “Alas!” he replied, shaking his head. “The doubt regarding when I might manage to come back! I shall strive for it with such fervor! It will be the focus of all my plans and concerns! And if my aunt and uncle travel to the city this spring—though I fear—they did not move last spring—I worry that habit is lost forever.” “Our unfortunate dance must be entirely abandoned.” “Oh, that dance! Why did we delay for anything? Why not grasp the joy immediately? How frequently is contentment ruined by planning, senseless planning! You warned us it would happen. Oh, Miss Woodhouse, why are you invariably correct?” “Truly, I regret being accurate in this case. I would much prefer to have been cheerful than clever.” “If I can return, we shall still hold our dance. My father counts on it. Do not forget your promise.” Emma offered a kind smile. “What a fortnight it has been!” he added. “Each day more valuable and enjoyable than the last! Each day making me less capable of enduring any other location. Fortunate are those who can stay in Highbury!” “Since you offer us such generous praise now,” Emma said with a laugh, “I will dare to inquire if you did not arrive with some hesitation at first? Do we not exceed your anticipations? I am certain we do. I am certain you did not expect to enjoy our company much. You would not have delayed your arrival so long if you had held a favorable view of Highbury.” He chuckled with a sense of self-awareness; and although he refuted the notion, Emma remained certain that it had been the case. “And you must depart this very morning?” “Indeed; my father is to meet me here: we shall walk back in company, and I must leave at once. I fear that any moment he might appear.” “Not five minutes to spare even for your acquaintances Miss Fairfax and Miss Bates? How unfortunate! Miss Bates’s vigorous, logical intellect might have bolstered your own.” “Yes—I have visited there; as I passed the door, I decided it was for the best. It was the proper action. I entered for three minutes, and was held up by Miss Bates’s absence. She was away; and I felt I could not leave until she returned.”"
}

