 stay in Highbury!” “Since you offer us such generous praise now,” Emma said with a laugh, “I will dare to inquire if you did not arrive with some hesitation at first? Do we not exceed your anticipations? I am certain we do. I am certain you did not expect to enjoy our company much. You would not have delayed your arrival so long if you had held a favorable view of Highbury.” He chuckled with a sense of self-awareness; and although he refuted the notion, Emma remained certain that it had been the case. “And you must depart this very morning?” “Indeed; my father is to meet me here: we shall walk back in company, and I must leave at once. I fear that any moment he might appear.” “Not five minutes to spare even for your acquaintances Miss Fairfax and Miss Bates? How unfortunate! Miss Bates’s vigorous, logical intellect might have bolstered your own.” “Yes—I have visited there; as I passed the door, I decided it was for the best. It was the proper action. I entered for three minutes, and was held up by Miss Bates’s absence. She was away; and I felt I could not leave until she returned.”"
}

model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "AUSTEN_EMMA_019",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "Woodhouse, I truly wish you had listened to the charming remarks he made to me during dinner. I tell you, I started to imagine my dear husband might grow quite envious. I suspect I am something of a favorite; he even remarked upon my dress. What is your opinion of it? It was selected by Selina; it is attractive, I suppose, though I wonder if it is perhaps too heavily decorated. I possess a profound aversion to being overly adorned—I have a genuine dread of excessive finery. I am obliged to wear a few decorations now, as it is anticipated of me. A bride, as you are aware, must look the part, yet my own inclination leans entirely toward modesty; a plain manner of dressing is so vastly superior to ostentation. However, I seem to be in the minority; few individuals appear to appreciate understated attire—display and ornamentation are everything. I am considering adding a trimming similar to this one to my white and silver poplin. Do you believe it will be becoming?”\n\nThe entire group had only just gathered again in the parlor when Mr. Weston arrived. Having returned for a belated dinner, he walked to Hartfield immediately afterward. He was anticipated by the most discerning observers, so his arrival caused no shock, yet it brought great delight. Mr. Woodhouse was nearly as pleased to welcome him now as he would have been distressed to see him earlier. John Knightley alone remained in silent disbelief. That a gentleman who could have passed his evening peacefully at home following a day of professional duties in London would depart once more, walking half a mile to another person’s residence just to endure social interaction until bedtime, and to conclude his day amidst the exertion of politeness and the clamor of a crowd, was a fact that profoundly affected him. A man who had been active since eight in the morning and could have been resting, who had been speaking at length and could have been quiet, who had been in multiple throngs and could have been solitary! For such a man to abandon the peace and autonomy of his own hearth, and on the evening of a chilly, sleety April day, to venture out into the world again! Had he been able to retrieve his wife with a mere gesture, there would have been a reason; yet his arrival would likely extend rather than conclude the gathering. John Knightley observed him with wonder, then lifted his shoulders and remarked, “I could not have credited it, even of him.”\n\nMr. Weston, meanwhile, entirely unaware of the resentment he was provoking, remained as joyful and buoyant as ever. Possessing the prerogative of being the primary speaker, which a day spent away from home provides, he was making himself pleasant to the others. Having answered his wife’s questions regarding his meal, assuring her that none of her meticulous instructions to the staff had been overlooked, and sharing whatever public news he had gathered, he moved on to a private matter. Although intended primarily for Mrs. Weston, he had no doubt it would be of great interest to everyone present. He handed her a letter; it was from Frank, addressed to her. He had encountered it on his journey and had taken the liberty of breaking the seal."
}

