model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "AUSTEN_EMMA_019",
  "condition": "modernize",
  "rewritten_text": "Mr. Woodhouse, I wish you had heard his charming compliments to me at dinner. Oh, I assure you, I began to think my dear husband would be truly jealous. I imagine I am quite a favorite; he even noticed my dress. How do you like it? It was Selina’s choice—handsome, I think, though I am not sure if it is a bit over-decorated. I have a real dislike for the idea of being over-decorated—I have a genuine horror of excessive finery. I have to wear a few ornaments now because it is expected of me. A bride, you know, must look like a bride, but my natural taste is for simplicity; a simple style of dress is so much better than being overly ornate. But I am in the minority, I suppose; few people seem to value simple dressing—show and finery are everything. I am thinking of adding a trim like this to my white and silver poplin. Do you think it will look good?”\n\nThe group had only just gathered in the drawing-room when Mr. Weston appeared. He had returned for a late dinner and walked to Hartfield as soon as he finished. He had been expected by those who knew him best, so there was no surprise—but there was great joy. Mr. Woodhouse was almost as happy to see him now as he would have been sorry to see him earlier. John Knightley, however, was struck with silent astonishment. That a man who could have spent his evening quietly at home after a day of business in London would set off again, walking half a mile to another man’s house just to be in a crowd until bedtime, finishing his day with the effort of being polite and the noise of a group, was a situation that deeply baffled him. A man who had been active since eight in the morning and could have been resting, who had been talking all day and could have been silent, who had been in more than one crowd and could have been alone! For such a man to leave the peace and independence of his own fireplace, and on the evening of a cold, sleety April day, rush back out into the world! If he could have instantly taken his wife home with a snap of his fingers, there would have been a motive, but his arrival would likely prolong the party rather than end it. John Knightley looked at him with amazement, then shrugged his shoulders and said, “I could not have believed it, even of him.”\n\nMr. Weston, meanwhile, completely unaware of the frustration he was causing, remained as happy and cheerful as ever. Exercising the right to be the main speaker that a day spent away from home provides, he made himself agreeable to everyone. After satisfying his wife’s questions about his dinner, assuring her that none of her careful instructions to the servants had been ignored, and sharing the public news he had heard, he moved on to a family matter. Although he addressed it primarily to Mrs. Weston, he had no doubt it would be highly interesting to everyone in the room. He handed her a letter; it was from Frank, addressed to her. He had picked it up on his way and taken the liberty of opening it."
}

