  "rewritten_text": "The instant she was freed from him was pure delight. She danced next with an officer, enjoying the relief of discussing Wickham and learning that he was held in general esteem. Once those dances concluded, she rejoined Charlotte Lucas, and while they were chatting, she was abruptly approached by Mr. Darcy. His request for her hand caught her so off guard that, acting without thought, she agreed. He departed at once, leaving her to lament her lack of composure; Charlotte attempted to offer comfort. \"I am certain you will discover him to be quite pleasant.\" \"Heaven forbid! That would be the ultimate calamity! To find a man agreeable whom I am resolved to detest! Do not wish such a misfortune upon me.\" When the music resumed and Darcy drew near to claim her, Charlotte whispered a warning not to be foolish, urging her not to let her preference for Wickham make her seem disagreeable to a man of his stature. Elizabeth remained silent as she took her position, struck by the significance of standing across from Mr. Darcy, and observing the matching surprise on the faces of those around them. They remained quiet for a while; she initially assumed their silence would persist throughout the set and decided not to interrupt it, until she suddenly thought it would be a greater penalty for her partner to force him into conversation, so she offered a brief comment about the dance. He answered, then fell silent again. After a few minutes, she spoke to him once more: \"It is your turn to speak now, Mr. Darcy. I commented on the dance, so you should offer some remark regarding the room's size or the number of guests.\" He smiled, promising to say whatever she desired. \"Very well; that answer suffices for now. Perhaps later I might mention that private parties are more enjoyable than public ones, but for now, we may remain quiet.\" \"Do you follow a set of rules while you dance, then?\" \"Occasionally. One must speak a little, after all. It would seem strange to remain entirely mute for half an hour; yet, for the benefit of some, conversation should be structured so they have the burden of saying as little as possible.\" \"Are you considering your own preferences here, or do you believe you are pleasing mine?\" \"Both,\" Elizabeth answered playfully, \"for I have always noticed a strong likeness in our temperaments. We both possess unsociable, reserved natures, reluctant to speak unless we anticipate saying something that will astonish the entire room and be remembered by future generations with the brilliance of a proverb.\" \"This is not a very accurate depiction of your own character, I am certain,\" he remarked. \"How close it might be to mine, I cannot say. You surely believe it to be an accurate likeness.\" \"I must not be the judge of my own work.\""
}

