nge to be completely silent for half an hour. Yet, for the benefit of some people, conversation should be arranged so they have the trouble of saying as little as possible.\" \"Are you considering your own feelings, or do you imagine you are pleasing mine?\" \"Both,\" Elizabeth replied playfully, \"for I have always noticed a great similarity in our minds. We are both unsocial and quiet, unwilling to speak unless we expect to say something that will amaze the whole room and be remembered forever like a famous proverb.\" \"This is not a very accurate description of your own character, I am sure,\" he said. \"How close it is to mine, I cannot say. You certainly think it is a faithful portrait.\" \"I must not judge my own performance.\""
