 a tour of the house, likely pleased to show it off without her husband’s interference. It was small, but well-built and convenient. Everything was arranged with a neatness and consistency for which Elizabeth gave Charlotte full credit. When Mr. Collins could be ignored, the house felt very comfortable, and judging by Charlotte’s obvious enjoyment, Elizabeth assumed he must be ignored quite often.\n\nShe had already learned that Lady Catherine was still in the area. The subject came up again during dinner, when Mr. Collins joined in, remarking, “Yes, Miss Elizabeth, you will have the honor of seeing Lady Catherine de Bourgh at church this coming Sunday, and I need not say that you will be delighted by her. She is full of kindness and grace, and I have no doubt that you will be honored with some of her attention once the service is over. I have little hesitation in saying that she will include you and my sister Maria in every invitation she extends to us during your stay.”"
