  "rewritten_text": "This explained to Elizabeth why Mr. Wickham had been in their company. Mrs. Reynolds then pointed them toward a portrait of Miss Darcy, painted when she was but eight years of age. “And is Miss Darcy as beautiful as her brother?” Mr. Gardiner inquired. “Oh, indeed—the most beautiful young lady ever beheld; and so talented! She performs music all day long. In the adjoining room sits a new instrument recently arrived for her—a gift from my master: she arrives here tomorrow with him.” Mr. Gardiner, whose demeanor was relaxed and agreeable, prompted her talkativeness with his inquiries and comments; Mrs. Reynolds, whether from vanity or devotion, clearly took great delight in speaking of her employer and his sister. “Does your master spend much time at Pemberley throughout the year?” “Not as much as I might desire, sir: yet I expect he spends half his time here; and Miss Darcy always visits for the summer months.” “Except,” Elizabeth mused, “when she travels to Ramsgate.” “If your master were to marry, you might see him more often.” “Yes, sir; but I cannot say when that might occur. I do not know who is worthy of him.” Mr. and Mrs. Gardiner exchanged smiles. Elizabeth could not refrain from remarking, “It is certainly to his credit that you hold such an opinion.” “I speak only the truth, and what anyone who knows him would confirm,” the woman answered. Elizabeth felt this was an exaggeration; she listened with growing surprise as the housekeeper continued, “I have never received an unkind word from him in my life, and I have known him since he was four years old.” This was praise of the most unusual kind, entirely contrary to her own perceptions. That he was a man of poor temper had been her most settled conviction. Her interest was fully piqued: she desired to hear more, and felt thankful to her uncle for observing, “There are very few individuals of whom such things can be said. You are fortunate to have such a master.” “Yes, sir, I am well aware of it. If I were to travel the world, I could not find a better one. But I have always noted that those who are kind-natured as children remain so as adults; and he was always the most sweet-tempered, generous-hearted boy imaginable.” Elizabeth nearly stared at her. “Can this truly be Mr. Darcy?” she wondered. “His father was a wonderful man,” Mrs. Gardiner noted. “Yes, ma’am, he certainly was; and his son will be just like him—equally gracious to the poor.” Elizabeth listened, marveled, doubted, and craved further information. Mrs. Reynolds could capture her attention on no other topic. She described the themes of the paintings, the size of the chambers, and the cost of the furnishings to no avail. Mr. Gardiner, quite entertained by the sort of domestic bias to which he ascribed her glowing praise of her master, soon steered the conversation back to the subject; and she spoke with vigor regarding his many virtues as they walked together up the grand staircase. “He is the finest landlord and the finest master,” she declared, “that ever existed. Unlike the reckless young men of today, who consider only their own interests. There is not a single tenant or servant of his who would not speak well of him.”"
