  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "“Well, miss?” I replied, nearly stumbling into her before catching my balance. She remained there observing me, and naturally, I remained there observing her. “Am I pretty?” “Yes; I believe you are quite pretty.” “Am I insulting?” “Not quite as much as you were previously,” I remarked. “Not quite as much?” “No.” She flared up at that final inquiry, and she struck my face with all the strength she possessed when I gave my response. “Now?” she demanded. “You small, vulgar beast, what is your opinion of me now?” “I refuse to say.” “Because you intend to report it upstairs. Is that the reason?” “No,” I replied, “that is not the reason.” “Why do you not weep again, you small wretch?” “Because I shall never weep for you again,” I stated. This was, I imagine, as untruthful a statement as was ever uttered; for I was weeping internally for her at that very moment, and I am aware of the suffering she caused me in later years. We proceeded toward the stairs following this encounter; and, as we ascended, we encountered a man feeling his way downward. “Who have we here?” the man inquired, pausing to examine me. “A boy,” Estella replied. He was a stout individual with an exceptionally swarthy complexion, possessing an unusually massive head and a hand of matching proportions. He gripped my chin with his heavy hand and tilted my face upward to inspect me by the candlelight. He was balding early at the crown of his head and featured thick, dark eyebrows that refused to lie flat, instead standing up in bristles. His eyes were deeply sunken, appearing unpleasantly keen and distrustful. He wore a heavy watch-chain and displayed dark, coarse pores where his beard and sideburns would have appeared had he allowed them to grow. He meant nothing to me, and I could have had no premonition then that he would ever hold significance for me, yet it occurred that I had this chance to study him closely. “A local boy? Eh?” he asked. “Yes, sir,” I replied. “How did you arrive here?” “Miss Havisham summoned me, sir,” I clarified. “Very well! Conduct yourself properly. I possess a rather extensive knowledge of boys, and you are a troublesome group. Now take heed!” he said, gnawing the side of his thick forefinger while scowling at me, “see that you behave!” With those remarks, he let me go—which I welcomed, as his hand carried the scent of perfumed soap—and continued his descent. I pondered if he might be a physician; but no, I reasoned; he could not be a doctor, or he would possess a more gentle and convincing demeanor. There was little time to dwell on the matter, for we soon reached Miss Havisham’s chamber, where she and all the surroundings remained exactly as I had left them. Estella abandoned me near the entrance, and I remained there until Miss Havisham turned her gaze toward me from the vanity. “So!” she remarked, showing no sign of alarm or astonishment: “the days have passed, have they?” “Yes, ma’am. Today is—” “There, there, there!” she interrupted with an impatient flick of her fingers. “I have no desire to know. Are you prepared to play?” I was forced to reply in some disarray, “I do not believe I am, ma’am.”"
}

