  "passage_id": "DICKENS_GREAT_EXPECTATIONS_011",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "I discovered then that Wemmick served as the clerk in the adjacent office. A different clerk was summoned from the upper floor to relieve him during his absence, and I walked out with him after bidding my guardian farewell. A fresh crowd of individuals waited outside, but Wemmick cleared a path by stating calmly yet firmly, “I tell you it is pointless; he will not speak to any of you;” we quickly moved past them and proceeded together. Chapter XXI. Observing Mr. Wemmick as we walked to gauge his appearance in the daylight, I saw a dry man of modest height, possessing a square, wooden face that looked as though it had been roughly carved by a blunt tool. There were indentations that might have been dimples had the surface been more yielding and the carving implement sharper, but they remained mere dints. The chisel had attempted a few such decorations near his nose before abandoning the task. I surmised he was unmarried due to his worn shirt cuffs, and he seemed to have endured many losses, as he sported at least four mourning rings and a brooch depicting a woman weeping by a tomb beneath a willow tree. I also observed various seals and rings dangling from his watch-chain, suggesting he was heavily burdened with tokens of deceased acquaintances. His eyes were bright, small, sharp, and dark, and his lips were thin, wide, and spotted. He had possessed them, I estimated, for forty to fifty years. “So you have never visited London previously?” Mr. Wemmick inquired. “No,” I replied. “I was a newcomer here once,” Mr. Wemmick remarked. “Strange to consider now!” “You are quite familiar with it at present?” “Well, yes,” Mr. Wemmick answered. “I understand how it functions.” “Is it a very sinful city?” I asked, mostly to keep the conversation going. “You might be swindled, plundered, or killed in London. But there are plenty of people everywhere willing to do that for you.” “If there is animosity between you and them,” I suggested, attempting to temper the statement. “Oh! I am not sure about animosity,” Mr. Wemmick replied; “there is not much of that involved. They will do it if there is profit to be made.” “That makes it more severe.” “You believe so?” Mr. Wemmick countered. “Much the same, I would argue.” He kept his hat pushed back and stared ahead, walking with a detached air as if the streets held no interest for him. His mouth was shaped like a post-office slot, giving him the mechanical look of a smile. We reached the summit of Holborn Hill before I realized it was merely a physical quirk and he was not actually smiling. “Do you know where Mr. Matthew Pocket resides?” I asked Mr. Wemmick. “Yes,” he said, gesturing toward the area. “In Hammersmith, to the west of London.” “Is that a great distance?”"
}

