  "passage_id": "DICKENS_GREAT_EXPECTATIONS_013",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "I then inquired if there were many clerks, to which he answered, “We don’t employ many, as there is only one Jaggers, and clients refuse to deal with anyone else. There are just four of us. Would you care to meet them? You are, in a sense, one of us.” I agreed. After Mr. Wemmick finished mailing the biscuits and handed me my funds from a safe—retrieving the key from his coat collar like a metallic pigtail—we ascended the stairs. The building was dim and dilapidated, and the oily stains on the walls suggested years of heavy traffic. In the front room on the first floor, a clerk resembling a cross between a tavern keeper and a rat-catcher—a large, pale, bloated man—was busy with several disheveled individuals, whom he handled with the same lack of courtesy shown to everyone who paid Mr. Jaggers. “Gathering testimony,” Mr. Wemmick remarked as we exited, “for the Old Bailey.” In the room above, a small, limp clerk with unkempt hair was occupied with a weak-eyed man whom Wemmick introduced as a smelter who kept his furnace running constantly and could melt anything; the man was sweating profusely, as if he had been testing his craft on his own person. In a rear office, a man with hunched shoulders and a jaw wrapped in soiled flannel, wearing aged black garments that looked waxed, was bent over his task of transcribing the notes of the other two for Mr. Jaggers’s review. This constituted the entire staff. Upon returning downstairs, Wemmick guided me into my guardian’s office and noted, “You have already seen this.” “Tell me,” I asked, as the two repulsive casts with their twitching expressions came into view, “whose portraits are those?” “These?” Wemmick replied, climbing onto a chair and dusting off the grotesque heads before lowering them. “These are two renowned figures. Famous clients who brought us great prestige. This fellow—you must have snuck in at night and peered into the inkwell to get that smudge on your brow, you old scoundrel!—killed his master, and for someone untrained in legal matters, he planned it quite well.” “Is it an accurate likeness?” I inquired, pulling back from the brute as Wemmick spat on its eyebrow and wiped it with his sleeve. “Accurate? It is the man himself. The mold was taken at Newgate immediately after he was removed from the gallows. You had a particular fondness for me, didn’t you, Old Artful?” Wemmick then clarified this affectionate address by pointing to his brooch, which depicted a lady and a weeping willow beside a tomb with an urn, stating, “Had it commissioned specifically for me!” “Is the lady someone in particular?” I asked. “No,” Wemmick replied. “Just his little joke. (You enjoyed your bit of fun, didn’t you?)"
}

