model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "DICKENS_GREAT_EXPECTATIONS_021",
  "condition": "simplify",
  "rewritten_text": "What then, once that is done? Here I am. To go back now would be as bad as standing still—or worse. Besides, Pip, I am here because I have intended to do right by you for years and years. As for what I dare, I am an old bird now, having survived all kinds of traps since I first learned to fly, and I am not afraid to land on a scarecrow. If death is hidden inside it, so be it; let it come out, and I will face it, and only then will I believe in it. Now, let me have another look at my gentleman.\" Once more, he took me by both hands and looked me over with an air of admiring ownership, smoking with great satisfaction the entire time. It seemed to me that I could do nothing better than find him some quiet lodging nearby, which he could move into when Herbert returned, whom I expected in two or three days. It was clear to me that the secret had to be shared with Herbert, even if I ignored the immense relief I would feel by confiding in him. However, this was not at all clear to Mr. Provis (I decided to call him by that name), who refused to agree to Herbert’s involvement until he had seen him and formed a favorable opinion of his face. \"And even then, dear boy,\" he said, pulling a greasy little black Bible with a clasp out of his pocket, \"we will have him take an oath.\" To say that my terrifying patron carried this little black book around the world solely to make people swear on it in emergencies would be to claim something I never quite proved; but I can say that I never saw him use it for anything else. The book itself looked as if it had been stolen from a courtroom, and perhaps his knowledge of its history, combined with his own experiences, made him rely on its power as a kind of legal charm. When he produced it for the first time, I remembered how he had made me swear loyalty in the churchyard long ago, and how he had described himself last night as always swearing to his resolutions while in solitude. As he was currently dressed in a sailor’s outfit, in which he looked as if he had parrots and cigars to sell, I next discussed what clothes he should wear. He held an extraordinary belief in the effectiveness of knee-breeches as a disguise, and he had imagined an outfit for himself that would have made him look like a cross between a dean and a dentist. It was with considerable difficulty that I convinced him to wear clothes more like those of a prosperous farmer; we also arranged that he should cut his hair short and wear a little powder. Finally, since he had not yet been seen by the laundress or her niece, he was to stay out of their sight until he had changed his clothes. It might seem like a simple matter to decide on these precautions, but in my dazed, if not distracted, state, it took so long that I did not get out to carry them out until two or three in the afternoon."
}

