model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "DICKENS_OLIVER_TWIST_009",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "Bumble, having swapped his tricorne for a round hat and wrapped himself in a blue overcoat featuring a cape, climbed onto the coach exterior alongside the paupers whose legal residence was in question, eventually reaching London with them. He faced no difficulties during the journey other than the stubborn conduct of the two paupers, who kept shivering and grumbling about the chill in a way that Mr. Bumble claimed made his own teeth chatter and left him feeling uneasy, despite his heavy coat. After securing these troublesome individuals for the evening, Mr. Bumble settled into the inn where the coach halted and enjoyed a modest meal of steaks, oyster sauce, and porter. Placing a glass of steaming gin-and-water upon the mantel, he pulled his seat toward the hearth and, while musing on the widespread vice of ingratitude and grumbling, prepared to peruse the newspaper. The initial paragraph that caught Mr. Bumble’s gaze was this notice: “FIVE GUINEAS REWARD. Whereas a young lad named Oliver Twist vanished, or was lured away, last Thursday evening from his residence in Pentonville and has not been located since. The stated reward will be granted to anyone providing details that lead to finding the said Oliver Twist or shedding light on his background, in which the advertiser is, for various reasons, deeply concerned.” There followed a detailed account of Oliver’s clothing, physical traits, appearance, and departure, along with Mr. Brownlow’s full name and residence. Mr. Bumble widened his eyes, studied the notice deliberately three times, and within five minutes was heading toward Pentonville, having in his agitation abandoned his glass of hot gin-and-water untouched. “Is Mr. Brownlow in?” Mr. Bumble asked the young woman who answered the door. She offered the typical, somewhat evasive response: “I cannot say; where are you from?” As soon as Mr. Bumble mentioned Oliver’s name to explain his business, Mrs. Bedwin, who had been eavesdropping by the parlor entrance, rushed into the hallway, gasping for air. “Enter, please enter,” the elderly woman urged. “I was certain we would receive news of him. Dear boy! I knew it! I was positive. Bless him! I maintained that all along.” With these words, the kind woman hurried back to the parlor and, sinking onto a sofa, began to weep. The servant, less emotional, had meanwhile gone upstairs and returned to ask Mr. Bumble to follow her at once, which he did. He was ushered into the small rear study, where Mr. Brownlow and his companion, Mr. Grimwig, sat with decanters and glasses. The latter man immediately cried out, “A beadle. A parish beadle, or I shall consume my own head.” “Please do not interrupt for the moment,” Mr. Brownlow requested. “Kindly take a chair.” Mr. Bumble sat, thoroughly bewildered by Mr. Grimwig’s strange behavior. Mr. Brownlow adjusted the lamp to get a clear look at the beadle’s face and remarked with slight impatience, “Now, sir, you are here because you saw the advertisement?”"
}

