model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "DICKENS_OLIVER_TWIST_017",
  "condition": "paraphrase",
  "rewritten_text": "He would accompany Mrs. Maylie and Rose, listening to their literary discussions, or perhaps sit nearby in a shaded spot while the young woman read aloud—a task he could have watched until the fading light obscured the print. Afterward, he prepared his lessons for the following day, laboring diligently in a small chamber overlooking the garden until dusk arrived. Then, the ladies would stroll outside again, and he would join them, finding such joy in their conversation and such delight in retrieving a flower he could climb to reach or fetching an item they had misplaced, that he could never move fast enough to serve them. Once darkness fell and they went indoors, the young lady would play the piano, performing a pleasant melody or singing a soft, old song that her aunt enjoyed. During these moments, they left the candles unlit, and Oliver would remain by the window, enraptured by the beautiful music.\n\nSundays were spent in a manner entirely unlike any he had previously known, yet they were just as joyful as every other day during that blissful period. In the morning, there was the small church, where green leaves rustled at the windows, birds chirped outside, and the fragrant air drifted through the low entrance, perfuming the simple structure. The parishioners appeared so tidy and knelt with such devotion that their gathering felt like a genuine pleasure rather than a tiresome obligation. Although the singing may have been unrefined, it was sincere, sounding more melodic to Oliver than any church music he had previously encountered. Afterward, they took their customary walks, visiting the neat homes of the laborers. In the evening, Oliver read a few chapters from the Bible he had studied throughout the week, a task that filled him with more pride and satisfaction than if he had been the minister himself.\n\nEach morning, Oliver was up by six, wandering the fields and searching the hedges far and wide for bouquets of wildflowers. He would return home carrying his findings, which he arranged with great thought and care to decorate the breakfast table. He also gathered fresh groundsel for Miss Maylie’s birds, decorating their cages with the refined taste he had acquired under the village clerk’s expert guidance. Once the birds were groomed for the day, he usually had some small charitable errand to perform in the village. If not, he might play cricket on the green, or tend to the garden plants, a skill he had also learned from his mentor, who was a gardener by profession. He applied himself to these chores with genuine enthusiasm until Miss Rose appeared, at which point she would offer him endless praise for all he had accomplished."
}

