model_content:
{
  "passage_id": "DICKENS_OLIVER_TWIST_018",
  "condition": "modernize",
  "rewritten_text": "Oliver thought he heard him sob more than once, but he was afraid to interrupt him with any new comment—as he could easily guess what he was feeling—and so he stood aside, pretending to be busy with his bouquet. During this time, Mr. Giles, wearing his white nightcap, had been sitting on the steps of the carriage, resting an elbow on each knee and wiping his eyes with a blue cotton handkerchief covered in white dots. That the honest man had not been faking his emotion was clearly proven by the very red eyes with which he looked at the young gentleman when he turned around to speak to him. \"I think you should go on to my mother’s in the carriage, Giles,\" he said. \"I would rather walk slowly so I can have a little time before I see her. You can tell her I am coming.\" \"I beg your pardon, Mr. Harry,\" said Giles, giving his ruffled face a final wipe with the handkerchief, \"but if you would let the driver say that, I would be very grateful. It wouldn't be appropriate for the maids to see me in this state, sir; I would never have any authority over them again if they did.\" \"Well,\" Harry Maylie replied with a smile, \"you can do as you like. Let him go on with the luggage if you wish, and you can follow with us. But first, swap that nightcap for something more appropriate, or we will be taken for madmen.\" Reminded of his unbecoming attire, Mr. Giles snatched off his nightcap, tucked it away, and replaced it with a serious, sober-looking hat he pulled from the carriage. With that done, the driver left, and Giles, Mr. Maylie, and Oliver followed at a leisurely pace. As they walked, Oliver glanced from time to time with great interest and curiosity at the newcomer. He appeared to be about twenty-five years old and of average height; his face was open and handsome, and his manner was relaxed and charming. Despite the difference in their ages, he bore such a strong resemblance to the old lady that Oliver would have had no trouble guessing their relationship, even if he hadn't already spoken of her as his mother. Mrs. Maylie was waiting anxiously to receive her son when he reached the cottage. The reunion was filled with great emotion on both sides. \"Mother!\" the young man whispered. \"Why didn't you write sooner?\" \"I did,\" Mrs. Maylie replied, \"but upon reflection, I decided to hold back the letter until I had heard Mr. Losberne’s opinion.\" \"But why,\" the young man asked, \"why risk what so nearly happened? If Rose had—I cannot say that word now—if this illness had ended differently, how could you ever have forgiven yourself? How could I ever have known happiness again?\" \"If that had been the case, Harry,\" said Mrs. Maylie, \"I fear your happiness would have been permanently destroyed, and your arrival here, whether a day sooner or later, would have mattered very, very little.\" \"And who can wonder if that is true, mother?\" the young man replied. \"Or why should I say 'if'? It is—it is—you know it, mother—you must know it!\""
}

