  "rewritten_text": "Two half-quartern loaves; a pound of the best fresh butter; a piece of double Gloucester cheese; and, to finish it all, some of the richest liquor you have ever tasted! After this praise, Master Bates pulled a full-sized, corked wine bottle from one of his large pockets. At the same time, Mr. Dawkins poured a glass of raw spirits from the bottle he was carrying, which the sick man swallowed without a moment’s hesitation. “Ah!” Fagin said, rubbing his hands with great satisfaction. “You will be fine, Bill; you will be fine now.” “Fine!” Mr. Sikes exclaimed. “I could have been finished off twenty times over before you would have done anything to help me. What do you mean by leaving a man in this state for three weeks or more, you false-hearted vagabond?” “Just listen to him, boys!” Fagin said, shrugging his shoulders. “And we came here to bring him all these beautiful things.” “The things are well enough in their way,” Mr. Sikes remarked, feeling slightly calmer as he looked over the table. “But what do you have to say for yourself? Why did you leave me here, feeling miserable, with no health, no money, and nothing else, and take no more notice of me all this time than if I were that dog? Drive him away, Charley!” “I have never seen such a funny dog as that,” Master Bates cried, doing as he was told. “He is smelling the food like an old lady going to market! That dog would make his fortune on the stage and revive the drama, too.” “Be quiet,” Sikes shouted as the dog retreated under the bed, still growling angrily. “What do you have to say for yourself, you withered old fence, eh?” “I was away from London for a week or more, my dear, working on a scheme,” the Jew replied. “And what about the other two weeks?” Sikes demanded. “What about the other two weeks that you left me lying here like a sick rat in a hole?” “I could not help it, Bill. I cannot go into a long explanation in front of company, but I could not help it, upon my honor.” “Upon your what?” Sikes growled with extreme disgust. “Here! One of you boys cut me a piece of that pie to take the taste of that out of my mouth, or it will choke me to death.” “Do not lose your temper, my dear,” Fagin urged submissively. “I have never forgotten you, Bill; never once.” “No! I bet you have not,” Sikes replied with a bitter grin. “You have been scheming and plotting every hour that I have laid here shivering and burning. You decided Bill was to do this, and Bill was to do that, and Bill was to do it all for very little money as soon as he got well, because he was poor enough for your work. If it had not been for the girl, I might have died.” “There now, Bill,” Fagin argued, eagerly grabbing at the word. “If it had not been for the girl! Who but poor old Fagin was the reason you had such a helpful girl around you?” “He is telling the truth there!” Nancy said, stepping forward quickly. “Let him be; let him be.” Nancy’s arrival changed the conversation, as the boys, receiving a sly wink from the cautious old Jew, began to offer her liquor. She only drank a little, however, while Fagin, acting unusually cheerful, gradually brought Mr. Sikes into the discussion."
}

